infoparam.name: UML Note
infoparam.value:
Original specification of the Initial Notification procedure
When initiated either by flight crew action or an automatic trigger, an ATS Facilities Notification Contact message is sent and Avionics Timer ATST1 is set. The aircraft AFN application then awaits an AFN Acknowledgement message from ground.
Subject to prior agreement with the service provider, the supplementary address field of the ATS Facilities Notification Contact Message may contain an abbreviation of the ATC center address to which the message should be delivered (such as the corresponding IATA or ICAO code).
If a successful AFN Acnowledgement message is received within the period of time of ATST1, a positive indication is given to the flight crew and timer ATST1 is cancelled. The AFN acknowledgement messsage will contain the full 7-character address of the ground AFN end-system. This address should be used in all subsequent AFN messages.
If the aircraft AFN receives an AFN acknowledgement message with a non-zero reason code or timer ATST1 expires, an error indication is given to the the flight crew.

If the aircraft AFN receives an AFN acknowledgement message with a non-zero reason code
or timer ATST1 expires, an error indication is given to the the flight crew.

textline.data: The IN procedure is a confirmed connection setup
procedure initiated by the pilot and developed on
top of a lossy network.
The connection set up procedure
shall implement the Initial Notification
procedure defined by the FANS specification.
The system shall enable an aircraft
to set up a connection with a control tower.

infoparam.value: Any connection request will eventually complete, either successfully or unsuccessfully.

textline.data: To keep the model of the user applications
as general as possible, the state machine
of the pilot (resp. of the controller) accepts all
the rendezvous offers from the board-level
protocol (resp. the ground-level protocol).
In other words, the user-level applications
are modeled as rendezvous acceptors.
This assumption and its derived assumptions
address the users of the FANS protocol layer.
The network will never corrupt or duplicate messages.
Nor it will desequence messages.
Transmission delay = 0 in both sense.
Assumption description:
Double-click to edit
The network may loss one type of message:
the CC issued by the ground station after the
controller has acknowledged the connection.
The network does not loose messages.
Only CCs may be lost.
The protocol bounds retransmissions to 3.
Would the procedure fail, the pilot and the controller will be informed.
Assumption description:
Double-click to edit
Message parameters such as the tower's address are
not represented. This contributes to make reachability
analysis converge.
